76561198002394860,Not Recommended,224740,26467509,"Posted: 6 November, 2016",all,Linto1234,"tl;dr Game is majorly under developed. UI + AI sucks, and the whole game is kind of a drag to play tbhGaslamp games made on of my favorite roguelikes in Dungeons of Dreadmore. It was an increadiably rare beast of a game that made a much more accessable and easier game, while keeping all the elements that make roguelikes appealing. Because of this, when it was announced that they would be making a colony simulator game along the lines of Dwarf Fortress, I was excited. Maybe they can take a game that like other roguelikes had been seen as impenatrable to new palyers, and make it accessable, while still maintaining many of the elements that made dwarf fortress compelling.Well, the short answer is no. I bought the game at the first early access release, and while it was bearly a game, I saw where it could go with work. It does not meet any of those areas I felt it could go. Firstly, the games social ""class"" system, which I originally thought was a cool idea, actually takes away from the game. This is because middle class ""overseers"" are the only ones that can actively perform tasks, and the lower class ""workers"" are only able to assist in the tasks that the overseer they are assigned to is doing. This ultimatelly means that the lower class citizens feel pointless as without an  overseer they wonder mindlessly around your colony doing nothing, taking up resources and beds. Secondly, the game originally promised a personality and social system, where people could become friends and the traits would perhaps clash with each other. In reality, I have yet to see a single person make a friend or enemy, and the traits by and large are just window dressing. They seem to have next to no actual bearing on the gameplay, bar from a few annoying exceptions that make your colonists just randomly go made for a day, and then go back to normal. It feels tacked on and pointless. There is a happiness system in game where a well decorated work and sleep environment will make people work for longer hours, but again it feels pointless, or just unimportant. All tasks get done, so it just becomes a nuisance that slows down the entire experience for no obvious reason.Thirdly, the whole game feels clunky and unfinished. Whether its the slightly weird looking buildings, to wardrobes going through the floor, to colonists acting more like robots that people, the lack of roads and so many other issues, the game feels like it needed 6 more months or possibly even a year of development before it would actually feel fun. Right now it feels like you fight the UI and AI to get resources for pointless projects that provide no satisfaction."
