,Recommended,224740,25773717,"Posted: 29 September, 2016",all,STGGrant,"I greatly enjoyedDungeons of Dredmorand so I picked up this game as soon as it came out of Early Access. It had promise in early Alpha, but wasn't satisfying over the long term—not unexpected, since it's an Early Access game.I just triedClockwork Empiresagain (Beta 54C), and the improvement is MASSIVE. The game is rich and satisfying, with an interesting late game, many different routes to success once your colony stabilizes, and increasingly-difficult combinations of biomes (maps, basically) that open up for replayability and challenge. The overall artistic style of the game comes through very strongly and positively, The delightful Gaslamp Games sense of humor is evident throughout, and manages to stay fresh through several replays, which is a particularly difficult task for any 'funny' game. And most importantly, the simulation feels good, and responds well to good player decisions (a big change from early Alpha.)Definitely recommended."
,Recommended,224740,26444892,"Posted: 5 November, 2016",all,Zyxenfryx,"Biased review incoming.Huge fan of Gaslamp games since the early days of Dungeons of Dredmor.Been playing this game on and off for several years and watching its development.Seeing lots of complaints on how ""lazy"" the AI is.  The AI isn't that lazy, but there are systems in place that if you don't notice them, they will appear lazy.  For example the overseers and workers all take breaks during the day.  The happier they are, the shorter breaks they take.  How do you make them happy?  This partially depends on the individual, they all have quirks.  However, there are things that will make all of them happy in general.  Things such as safety (well-armed militia), workplace quality, housing quality, food quality, and public services such as a pub and/or church.Also assigning more tasks than there are roaming (not assigned to a building) overseers, then it will feel like nothing is getting done.As I said earlier, I've been playing this game a long time.  I don't remember having to learn the fairly complex UI because at one point it wasn't that complex.  But that made it too difficult to get things done.  I know it has a steep learning curve, but every failure helps you understand how to do it better next time.  Entire population wiped out by bandits?  Should have worked on militia earlier, built more homes, or taken them out first.  Run out of food?  Make production more efficient by putting the kitchen right next to the farm, or build a naturalist's building and have them hunt for game.There are many routes to go in this game, most are up to personal preference.Also, the game has a pause button (spacebar) during which you can manage multiple things while the game-time is frozen.  Abuse this power.Bottom line:  If you have the time and patience, this game is great for long-term entertainment.  Enjoy the tongue-in-cheek nature and don't take it too seriously."
