76561198007029367,Recommended,224740,29234004,Posted: 13 January,all,PFC Calico,"Ok well, here is my 2 cents. I bought clockwork empires before release but not as early as some other people. I am going to recommend this game overall but with one major caveat. Onwards to my review!The concept is brilliant, a colony sim in a Lovecraftian steampunk nightmare.The concept is delivered well with plenty of building options, other denizens of the area to either destroy in xenophobic genocide or merely tolerate, a resource system that is a breath of fresh air in comparison to the traditional groups of nodes or tunnelling into the earth directly.The crop system appears to be missing alot however if you spend a little time with the diplomacy you will find that allied trading partners may bring the option to grow other plants from other biomes along with your own research in the laboratory.The science aspect is developed yet simple however leaves too much rng for my tastes with the initial research options, i feel a more traditional tree similar to the Civ games would be more suitable however, but still using the 3 focuses to make it a decision whether to subjegate using advanced military might or develop your money making power with cash crops and dominate in the diplomacy arena.Combat is simple affair with equipping your squads with different gear as you unlock and craft it and then either letting them patrol the general area or directing them to specific points, possibly having the choice of equipping individual squad members with different weapons .I know I am making suggestions but bear with me,The biggest problem with this game is the restrictive manpower assignment process.You have overseers or foremen and labourers. You assign an overseer to a position within a production building and then assign labourers. Any work that is being carried out will be completed but lets say your carpenters are finished work and are just loafing around but your farmers require more help getting the crop in this season or the colony requires a tidy up then the carpenters will not do anything other than what is in the order queue for the workshop.To solve this I would say that maybe having clearing and land flattening common to all trades but so low on the priority list that it is used as filler when they have nothing better to do.Some people have a problem with the fact that the game has released with either not enough content, or not enough of this that or the other. I feel that the negative reviews are doing the opposite of what the possible intent may be. I am reccommending this game on the fact that with continued support then only then can it grow.I enjoy playing this game and do not wish to see it die like so many other indie productions, however the community has been burned by too many time wasters and is now over critical of any independant producers by expecting games that require nothing more added to it at release, look at bethesda and fallout 4 when that released, EA with simcity, AAA producers make mistakes yet they have the monetry backing to weather a community backlash.Indie producers do not, and require a different form of criticsm, one where as a community we still recommend the hard work but still temper it with helpful criticsm.I appologise for the review turn rant but one of the biggest reasons indie games fail is because the community kills them.Why continue putting blood, sweat and tears into something to be put to the steak and burned."
