76561198078365647,Not Recommended,224740,23364407,"Posted: 3 June, 2016",all,handsomegrape,"Alright, this game is in beta supposedly, and according to the developers is nearing full release. It's an indie game and costs about 1/2 as much as the Witcher 3. So is it at least 1/2 as good a value as the witcher 3? No, not even one tenth. Is it polished enough to issue it as a finished game? No. In fact I would dare say it's currently in alpha.It's broken and rough, for instance if you go into the options menue you risk being overwhelmed by the plethora of choices, such as music; On or Off. That's right, On or Off. Do you want to change the volume? No problem, just exit onto the main menue and... Oh wait, you can't, you need to exit the game, then restart it, and THEN on that starting screen you can change the volume. But not much else. Every time the game loads, you're pretty much past the point of certain that is has crashed again (nothing moves, the music stops), and THEN it starts.Betas can work, as long as you've got a somewhat stable and solid setup. Clockwork Empires combines the helplessness and slow♥♥♥♥♥pace of the Settlers with a grueling difficulty level close to that of Banished. The AI or AS rather, is what you find yourself relying on, yet it fails again and again to complete even the simplest of tasks, creating bottlenecks and downward spirals for your colonies.I've seen them wasting days picking things  up and dropping them, picking them up and dropping them, again and again. And you wonder why that vital building project isn't being built, that's why. I've seen them pick up resources and then heading out into the wilderness to gather more of said resource. Because whenever I go out to gather stones, I always bring some heavy boulders with me, because why not. It only gets better when said colonist gets spooked by some wildlife, drops the resources in the middle of nowhere and runs back home empty handed. The cooks finish meals only to gobble them down the second after and just, wow. I could go on.There's no prioritizing certain projects, unless you want to pause every other project, and even then with a work crew assigned to do just about everything, they're still mostly Idle, chatting away, and eating ten times their body weight, doing pretty much everything except the one thing you need them to.In 10hours, I've played 2 Colonies. Only 2 you say? Yes, because this game is SLOW! There's no fastforward button, buildings are erected in real time, colonists plod along in a zombie like pace etc. In both cases I've found that starvation is very hard to counteract, mostly because you don't start with any staple crops. The first time I started in the arctics, could grow nothing but cabbages; they sowed, reaped, and ate the produce right away while standing in the fields, didn't have the time to process or stockpile it. Hunting is unreliable, foraging doesn't yield enough, so what to do.The second time I started on a savannah, got chilli, tea and sugar. Does any of those sound like staple crops to you? At first I thought I could get by on hunting, but no. The meat dropped by the giant beetles apparently taste horrid and doesn't satisfy, and in either case isn't plentiful enough. Not even when they go cannibalistic do they manage to fill their bellies. Apparently eating a whole human isn't enough to satisfy their hunger needs once they're starving!Despite my best efforts to get along with the fishpeople, one of my moronic colonists went and raided one of their hatching piles when I wasn't looking and hadn't told him to, and as a result, I now get constant, endless, raiding parties whittling away at my starving colonists. My colonists' staple diet now consists of fishpeople steaks. Which they hate, and are STILL starving.When you need overseers you get workers, when you need workers you get overseers. There's always too much/too little of either or, and they apparently rely on different conditions. For instance, I managed to get a -66 relationship standing with my own empire using a diplomacy office (I kept asking for food, apparently they didn't like that). So now I never get any overseers, which means that if one of my current overseers die, I'm pretty screwed. You can't promote workers into overseers or anything like that, they are special snowflakes and if they die, which usually you have zero control over, it can be really bad. Again with the unstoppable downward spirals.Oh and you can't name the workteams either. So you can end up with The Happy Soldiers tending to a cabbage patch, and until they get skilled enough in farming, there's no quick way to see what they are doing without clicking on them (usually it just says Idle anyways, lazy bums). I get it, you have a high soldiering skill, but you're farmers now so shut up and farm.The game has plenty of those catch 22 moments that prevents you from enjoying it. In the savannah, there's apparently very little stone to be had, but it isn't obvious at first glance and I didn't know just how limited the colonists were in how far away they can move. I figured I needed a trade office to get stone. Guess what the trade office required to be built? Yes, stone. In the end, I solved it, but it's one of those cases where there's no way you could have known that it was going to be an issue and could have prepared for it in advance, since nobody told you. If you see a bunch of stone piles scattered around, you probably figure, hey I got stone, no problem. But you don't realize how little those piles actually yield in the end. And the tutorial only gives a generic runthrough (no mention of how to solve the food problem though), same for every enviroment, when it clearly shouldn't be.And you need to build a kitchen to cook. How bout a camp fire, and some tents for shelter that degrade over time. Who sends out colonists to sleep on the dirt and without proper crops to grow, apparently these people.So TLDR; it isn't balanced properly. And being forced to rely on the slow and moronic AI while nothing really happens that requires your attention, makes it that the game could just as easily be on standby without you. It isn't FUN to play is what I'm getting at. I can see a lot of potential with the idea, but some serious work is required to get it to a functioning level, and since the devs have the audacity to charge this much for a broken alpha version of the game and dare to say it's almost close to being finished; makes it so that I strongly doubt it will ever reach that potential.I would be happy if you prove me wrong though, so by all means, aim to do just that. But for now, for this price and claiming that it's almost finished when it's clearly not, gets a downvote from me."
