76561198057992835,Not Recommended,224740,26607902,"Posted: 14 November, 2016",all,Avarasai,"UPDATE: Do not buy, this game is confirmed abandonware.I've had this game since fairly early in its EA period, and have watched it grow and develop along the way. I've logged a little more than 100 hours in-game; Some of these were incredibly enjoyable, others were immensely frustrating. For those who don't want to read my more detailed analysis, here is the summary of it all:1) The game does play more like an EA game than a full release.2) There are bugs and UI issues that should have been resolved.3) It would have flourished even more with another six months of development.4) It's still worth the money and the above doesn't take away from the fact that given the opportunity, I would purchase it again.It is undeniable that there are things that should have been fixed before release. It does crash, it does have blips and bumps in gameplay that are unpolished, and it does feel as though the game devs said ""good enough"" when they should have commited to another few months of work at the very least. It is difficult, mainly due to utilizing way too many system resources and code instability, to hit the 100 population mark. I acknowledge that these are still problems and ones that, for many people, are unacceptable to the point of asking for refunds or refusing to play. However, I have and will continue to recommend this game to friends. Here's why:- The graphics, sound and style are completely unique. I've logs thousands of hours in city builders and economy sims, as those are my favorite genres. There is nothing like it on the market. It's a genuinely unique game experience that has carved out its own niche. Given the complexity of it all, it's also likely to stay that way.- The bugs, while present, are few and far between. I tend to play fairly heavily modded games, so perhaps stability simply isn't something that I am used to. However, that being said, I have played 10+ hour marathons of this game without it crashing. I average maybe 1 CTD per 3-4 maps, and I've played several to the near-hundred population mark. With the auto-saves that are built in and enabled by default, I have never lost more than 5 or so minutes worth of work. I don't find it a deal-breaker at all.- It is challenging, and it can be unforgiving. For some, that might also be a deal-breaker. For me, that's the essence of fun. Mistakes you made in the earliest moments (I'm looking at you, 3-square-wide alleyways between my houses) will come back to haunt you, but it won't be until twelve, thirteen, or even twenty hours into a map. That tight little layout that you designed out on graph paper before you built a single building in-game? Yeah, that's going to be an absolute death trap when the bandit army comes calling and your villagers try to stampede through it in an attempt to escape.- It is varied. No two maps will ever play out the same. A cult might summon a fish-person army to sack your city in one game but your priest may lose his mind and torch your humble homestead in the next.-Ultimately, and this continues to be the driving sentiment behind my relatively positive outlook on the game, the devs actually do care about the player base. Every issue we rose in EA was met with a solution or a compromise, or at the very least an explanation. They're communicative, responsive, and timely about changes. These aren't people that are going to screw off in the next few months and abandon ship; Despite what people have said in the recent days about the devs simply getting bored of the game and dumping it, I've seen absolutely nothing to indicate that this is the end. Things will get better, and things will improve. I have complete faith in that."
